{% set basicCiteCode %}<p>My favorite book is <cite>The Great Gatsby</cite> by F. Scott Fitzgerald.</p>{% endset %}

{% set blockquoteCiteCode %}<figure>
  <blockquote>
    <p>It was the best of times, it was the worst of times.</p>
  </blockquote>
  <figcaption>&mdash; Charles Dickens, <cite>A Tale of Two Cities</cite></figcaption>
</figure>{% endset %}

{% set quotedCiteCode %}<p>I watched <cite class="quoted">The Shawshank Redemption</cite> last night.</p>
<p>The article <cite class="quoted">Why CSS is Awesome</cite> changed my perspective.</p>{% endset %}

{% set citeCssCode %}cite {
  font-style: italic;
}

/* Quoted variant — adds typographic quotes */
cite.quoted::before {
  content: "\201C"; /* left double quote */
}

cite.quoted::after {
  content: "\201D"; /* right double quote */
}{% endset %}

<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;cite&gt;</code> element represents the title of a creative work: a book, paper, essay, poem, song, film, TV show, game, painting, musical, exhibition, legal case, website, or blog post. It is rendered in italic by default.</p>
    <p>The element should contain only the title of the work, not the author's name (though the author can appear nearby).</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Book titles:</strong> <cite>The Great Gatsby</cite></li>
      <li><strong>Film/TV:</strong> <cite>Inception</cite>, <cite>Breaking Bad</cite></li>
      <li><strong>Music:</strong> Album titles like <cite>Abbey Road</cite></li>
      <li><strong>Art:</strong> <cite>Starry Night</cite>, <cite>The Thinker</cite></li>
      <li><strong>Games:</strong> <cite>The Legend of Zelda</cite></li>
      <li><strong>Attribution:</strong> Inside <code>&lt;figcaption&gt;</code> for blockquote sources</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>When NOT to Use</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>For author names alone &mdash; use plain text or <code>&lt;b&gt;</code></li>
      <li>For inline quotations &mdash; use <a href="/docs/elements/native/q/"><code>&lt;q&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For emphasis &mdash; use <a href="/docs/elements/native/em/"><code>&lt;em&gt;</code></a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Examples</h2>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/cite-examples.html" url="cite-examples.html" title="Citation examples" shadow></browser-window>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Inline citation">{{ basicCiteCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="With blockquote and figcaption">{{ blockquoteCiteCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Variants</h2>

    <h3><code>.quoted</code></h3>
    <p>Adds typographic double quotes around the title via CSS <code>::before</code> and <code>::after</code>. Useful when house style requires titles in quotes rather than (or in addition to) italics.</p>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Quoted cite variant">{{ quotedCiteCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CSS Reference</h2>
    <code-block language="css" show-lines label="Cite CSS">{{ citeCssCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><code>&lt;cite&gt;</code> has no special ARIA role &mdash; screen readers render it as italic text</li>
      <li>The semantic meaning helps search engines understand the text is a title</li>
      <li>The italic styling provides a visual convention familiar to readers</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Related Elements</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/blockquote/"><code>&lt;blockquote&gt;</code></a> &mdash; For longer quotations (cite provides the source title)</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/q/"><code>&lt;q&gt;</code></a> &mdash; For inline quotations with locale-aware quote marks</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/figure/"><code>&lt;figure&gt;</code></a> &mdash; For self-contained content with optional <code>&lt;figcaption&gt;</code></li>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/em/"><code>&lt;em&gt;</code></a> &mdash; For emphasis (not titles)</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/elements/native/i/"><code>&lt;i&gt;</code></a> &mdash; For alternate voice text (taxonomic names, thoughts)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
